<published>2011-06-14T08:55:36-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7860&amp;p=79781#p79781</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7860&amp;p=79781#p79781"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Confused at the scanline numbering in the wiki]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7860&amp;p=79781#p79781"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">mkwong98 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Does line 20 in the PPU_frame_timing page the same as pre-render line in PPU_ntsc_pal_difference page and the line -1 in PPU_rendering page?<br /></div><br />Yes.<br /><br />The convention that Nintendo hardware follows is that 0 starts the picture and line 241 starts the vblank. Evidence of the Nintendo convention comes from the <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/PPU_power_up_state" class="postlink">PPU power up state</a>, which appears to begin at the start of picture instead of the start of vblank, and the behavior of the <a href="http://wiki.superfamicom.org/snes/show/Registers#opvct__vertical_scanline_location_70" class="postlink">Super NES's OPVCT register</a> and the <a href="http://nocash.emubase.de/gbatek.htm#lcdiointerruptsandstatus" class="postlink">GBA's VCOUNT register</a>. Another convention, used mostly in the broadcasting industry, is that line 21 starts the picture and line 0 starts the vblank. I have been trying to follow Nintendo's convention when describing Nintendo's hardware. Thank you for pointing out that <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/PPU_frame_timing" class="postlink">PPU frame timing</a> does not follow Nintendo's convention. I have fixed this page.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Jun 14, 2011 8:55 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
